<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<section xml:id="inv-5-5">
  <title>Investigation 5.5: Restaurant Spending and Music</title>

  <exercises xml:id="exercises5-5" hidden-label="yes">
    <title>The Study</title>

    <sidebyside widths="62% 33%" margins="0% 0%" valign="top">
      <stack>
        <p>A British study (North, Shilcock, &amp; Hargreaves, <url href="https://www.researchgate.net/publication/249624546_The_Effect_of_Musical_Style_on_Restaurant_Customers'_Spending">2003</url>) examined whether the type of background music playing in a restaurant affected the amount of money that diners spent on their meals. The researchers asked a restaurant to alternate classical music, popular music, and silence on successive nights over 18 days.</p>
      </stack>
      <image source="images/restaurant.jpg" width="100%">
        <description>Restaurant setting for the Investigation 5.5 study context</description>
      </image>
    </sidebyside>

    <p>The following summary statistics about the total bills were reported:</p>

    <tabular halign="center" top="minor" bottom="minor" left="minor" right="minor">
      <row header="yes">
        <cell></cell>
        <cell>Classical music</cell>
        <cell>Pop music</cell>
        <cell>No music</cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell halign="left">Mean</cell>
        <cell>24.13</cell>
        <cell>21.91</cell>
        <cell>21.70</cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell halign="left">SD</cell>
        <cell>2.243</cell>
        <cell>2.627</cell>
        <cell>3.332</cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell halign="left">Sample size</cell>
        <cell><m>n_1=120</m></cell>
        <cell><m>n_2=142</m></cell>
        <cell><m>n_3=131</m></cell>
      </row>
    </tabular>

    <exercise xml:id="inv5-5-a" label="I5.5.a">
      <title>State Hypotheses</title>
      <statement>
        <p>State the null and alternative hypotheses corresponding to the researchers' conjecture (in symbols and/or in words, be sure to define any symbols you use).</p>
      </statement>
      <response/>
      <solution>
        <p><m>H_0</m>: the true treatment means <m>(\mu_{class} = \mu_{pop} = \mu_{none})</m> are all equal.</p>
        <p>Or <m>H_0</m>: the mean amounts spent in the long run are the same regardless of type of music being played.</p>
        <p><m>H_a</m>: at least one true treatment mean differs.</p>
        <p>Or <m>H_a</m>: at least one type of music shows a tendency for higher or lower spending amounts on average.</p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="inv5-5-b" label="I5.5.b">
      <title>Calculate Key ANOVA Quantities</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Based on these summary statistics, calculate:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><p>the overall (weighted) mean amount spent, <m>\bar{x} = \sum (n_i \bar{x}_i) / \sum n_i</m>,</p></li>
          <li><p>the between-group variation, <m>MSG = \sum n_i (\bar{x}_i - \bar{x})^2 / (I-1)</m>,</p></li>
          <li><p>and the pooled standard deviation, <m>MSE = \sum_{i = 1}^I (n_i - 1)s_i^2 / (n - I)</m>.</p></li>
        </ul>
        <p>Check the consistency of your calculations with the summary statistics reported above.</p>
      </statement>
      <response/>
      <solution>
        <p>weighted mean = <m>[120(24.13) + 142(21.91) + 131(21.70)]/(120+142+131) = 22.52</m> (this is in the "middle" of the 3 observed averages).</p>
        <p>Between group variability.</p>
        <p>Pooled variance = <m>[119(2.243^2)+141(2.627^2)+130(3.332^2)]/(119+141+130) = 7.73</m>.</p>
        <p>Pooled std dev = <m>\sqrt{7.73} = 2.78</m> (this is in the "middle" of the observed standard deviations).</p>
        <p>variability between groups = <m>120(24.13-22.52)^2 + 142(21.91-22.52)^2 + 132(21.7-22.52)^2/2 = 226</m>.</p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Technology Detour </title>

      <exercise xml:id="inv5-5-tech-detour-anova">
        <title>ANOVA Calculations</title>
        <statement>
          <p>Confirm your calculations using technology.</p>

          <hint>
            <title>Applet Instructions</title>
            <p>Use the <url href="http://www.rossmanchance.com/applets/2021/test/fCalc.htm"><em>F</em> Probability Calculator applet</url>.</p>
            <p>Enter your observed <m>F</m> value and use the upper-tail probability.</p>
          </hint>

          <hint>
            <title>R Instructions</title>
            <p>Use <c>pf(x, df1, df2, lower.tail=FALSE)</c> with <c>x = 29.2</c>, <c>df1 = 2</c>, and <c>df2 = 390</c>.</p>
          </hint>

          <hint>
            <title>JMP Instructions</title>
            <p>Use Distribution Calculator, choose <em>F</em>, and compute the upper-tail probability for <m>F = 29.2</m> with df 2 and 390.</p>
          </hint>

          <hint>
            <title>Expected Result</title>
            <p>You should obtain <m><em>F</em> = 226/7.73 = 29.2</m>. The p-value is approximately zero.</p>
          </hint>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </paragraphs>

    <exercise xml:id="inv5-5-c" label="I5.5.c">
      <title>Interpret Relative Variation</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Which appears to be larger, the variation in amount spent between diners or the variation in amount spent between types of music?</p>
      </statement>
      <response/>
      <solution>
        <p>The variation between types of music appears larger than the variation in amount spent between diners.</p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="inv5-5-d" label="I5.5.d">
      <title>Assess ANOVA Conditions</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Do you consider this p-value to be valid? In other words, are the technical conditions for ANOVA met for this study design?</p>
      </statement>
      <response/>
      <solution>
        <p>We would need to be able to verify the technical conditions (in fact, there is an issue here in that the treatments were assigned to the evenings and not the individual dinners).</p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>

    <assemblage xml:id="study-conclusions-5-5">
      <title>Study Conclusions</title>
      <p>The classical music nights had the largest sample mean spending. The reported ANOVA result (<m>F=31.48</m>, very small p-value) gives strong evidence of differences in group means. However, independence is questionable because treatments were assigned by evening rather than to individual diners, so evening-level effects may be confounded with music condition. Thus descriptive differences are clear, but causal interpretation and broader generalization require caution.</p>
    </assemblage>

  </exercises>

